segments.text: You tried to do.
First, when you got to the office, was there each morning?
Like Doctor Williams used to have his
they had his paperwork for him to sign first.
What did?
I think basically that was it, was get the paperwork.
But generally I was not a good dictator, so I hand wrote most of my papers and things of this sort.
I introduced the policy of reply by note.
In other words, somebody would send me a letter, and I'd insist that they just have one point into that note, yes, no, and I'd put a xerox it, and it goes.
Well, that took care of a lot of the responsibility in the mail.
During those years, who were your key office staff members?
Mary Ruth Patronella had to be listed as one.
Describe her work.
She probably knows more about the College of Agriculture today and then than anyone else.
And Elizabeth Williamson was a person.
These are two staff people that I've worked with.
Curtis Lard was in there and Dick Potts.
Bill Pope.
Did you appoint Ms. Patronella to?
Yeah, I appointed her.
I was associate director of the station, so I asked her to come over to be my secretary.
And Dr. Patterson liked her, and so he moved her over to the dean's office.
And so when I made dean, I moved over and joined her again.
Describe her manner.
HER MANNER IS ONE OF QUIET CONFIDENCE AND KNOWLEDGE.
SHE'S BRIGHT.
Vader is assistant to the dean.
I had a little trouble doing that because some of the folks that were running the classification system were
What was her manner of letting you know that she thought you might have made a mistake in a letter?
She'd tell me.
Is that right?
Yes.
She says, I think you want to change this.
Elizabeth Williamson did that too.
She says, I think you want to change this.
Did they have a good sense of humor?
Oh, yes.
And I didn't mind it.
You need to know me as a person.
I generally...
There are certain things that just irritated me.
Such as?
We can't do it.
And any time I says, oh, you can't do it, and I'd say, why?
And if the answer wasn't good, I'd blow my top.
But I'd cool down.
In that way, I was a little like John.
And so if things basically irritated me,
My ire was well known as far as this is concerned.
When you left the office each day, each work day, did you take paperwork home with you?
I took a briefcase home, but I didn't open it.
Okay.
What did you do in the evenings to relax?
Well, I eventually came to the point where I was following TV and
Had a drink or two.
Do you have any hobbies?
Any relaxation activities?
No, the only hobby I have is probably a little of photography when I take trips and things of that sort.
Because you're not a hunter, fisher, golfer, tennis.
I'm not a hunter, fisher, golfer or anything of the sort.
And you don't have a farm or anything like that?
No.
Let's see, church goer?
Church goer.
Where?
Holy Cross Lutheran Church.
Is that Evangelical or Missouri?
That's Missouri.
Missouri Synod.
And you grew up in Missouri Synod?
I grew up in Missouri Synod.
I've been a lifelong Missouri Synod member.
During those 20 years, about what percentage of the time were you on the road?
At least 10% of the time.
And where are some of the places overseas you went?
Wherever we had a project going.
South America, Sri Lanka, Africa, Saudi Arabia.
Well, only one trip to Saudi Arabia.
No, but I mean, did you go to East Pakistan, Bangladesh?
I went to East Pakistan or Bangladesh, yes.
Ever have any narrow escapes or scary moments on any of those trips?
Yes.
Where?
Well, my wife and I were in Africa, and we were...
Flying back to Nairobi, in Kenya, and the plane stopped off at a resort place just across the border.
And we had a Coke.
The pilot was one of them.
It turned out that a lady decided to go with us, and she had more baggage than anything else, so we turned out to be an overweighted plane.
And as we took off, there were three topis.
Antelope.
Excuse me.
And...
The pilot says, well, usually they get out of the way.
We'll see what they do.
And so we did, and the plane came up along with them.
As the plane caught up with them, one went this way, one went into the plane.
And the squawk button went off and things of the sort.
We landed.
We landed.
in between spaces in a hard-bark place, but we came back and we found out that the plane was grounded because they had, the wheels were pushed aside.
Oh, there were some interesting ones that I had.
I went into, I was going into Africa and I joined my
stepfather and mother-in-law, stepfather, mother-in-law, mother-in-law.
We landed at Johannesburg Airport and we were waiting, we were going up to Victoria Falls.
And they wouldn't take off.
until late when we got there, we found that Zambian terrorists had shot up the airport.
So I guess there are a few things of that sort to do.
Any zany experiences on any one of those trips?
Goofy?
I'm sorry?
Any zany, goofy?
I don't know.
On any of those trips?
Who are some of the celebrities that you met?
Most of the people were the people in the, well, celebrities.
Like you, emperors, kings?
No, I didn't.
I did, as a result of a project, go down and meet Borgiba, who was president of Tunisia at one time.
That was down in Houston.
We were about to meet with Queen Elizabeth and Prince Philip at Kandy, Sri Lanka, but we were called back to Colombo beforehand, so we missed that opportunity.
In overseas work, were there any projects that we missed that you wish we had been able to participate in?
Any near misses?
Well, I think there was a couple that we missed.
I thought we should have gone into Kenya and Edgerton College and worked with those folks.
We had a later opportunity to go with the agricultural, Bangladesh Agricultural University to go back in, and I think we missed that.
Which of all those are you most proud to
which of the projects?
Oh, I think the Bangladesh Agricultural University is the one that they had the greatest impact in.
But I think as far as foreign programs are concerned was the ones when we brought these young people in from the Dominican Republic.
And they generally went home and the Aggie Club became a political force.
And will be for years.
Here, in your long service, of what are you most proud here at A&M for your years of service?
Well, I think the research and extension center complex, which I put into place and focused on.
I think the movement of the College of Agriculture to the College of Agriculture and Life Sciences, literally, not just by name only, is one that I'm particularly proud of.
I think that in the later years after being dean, to establish, to work with and be a sort of a godfather to the movement of agricultural ethics in the country, that particular movement.
I think some of the early graduate work, undergraduate students that I advised, I'm particularly proud of.
Proud because of what they've gone on to achieve?
What they've gone on to do as far as this is concerned.
How did Aggie students change during your years here?
The fundamental change
It's a curious one, I can't explain it.
When the students came back after World War II and taught, and then back in the 50s taught, the students were, they would go to class.
They'd take 15, 16, 17 hours, take a full load.
I'd drink a beer every once in a while, but that would be about it.
They were very serious students.
Today, students take no more than 12 hours.
They just as soon have a class in which they don't have to go to class, the student.
Their education, what they seek from education, is not the same thing that we thought, or that the students in the 50s and 60s thought.
They were seeking technical knowledge.

The students here today are probably self-educating themselves or educating themselves more individually, which means, obviously, that a residential university is far better than this business of distance learning or whatever you want to call it.
I think that
In some ways, I guess they haven't changed, but there are some that are very interested in hard working and things of this sort.
There are some that have the major ability that they can grasp points.
Am I right?
Oh, I think so.
And also, I want to reach back.
You mentioned people like Dick Potts and Curtis Lard.
What was special about them?
counselors, advisors like that?
Well, particularly Dick Potts.
He believed that you helped people get through college.
And even if you put a dunderhead out, that dunderhead you'd never have to be embarrassed by.
And I guess basically he was right.
Am I correct that he knew when to make an exception to the rule and when not to?
That's correct, yeah.
And he was always patient?
He was always patient.
Let's see, other proud moments of all your years at A&M?
Any big research projects that you're particularly proud to have been a part of?
My research really never came to fruition.
But for the college, what about?
Oh, for the college, the biggest one is the so-called conversion project, where they took the grain sorghums of various sundry places and converted them just to things that could be used.
could be used for in crops and breeding and things of the sort for the United States.
I think that the major contribution that we did as far as the university is concerned is to change the structure of animal breeding, the meats projects as we have.
And currently, I think the introduction of molecular biology in the university I'm particularly happy with.
In hindsight, did we miss some opportunities?
Probably.
In agriculture?
Probably.
Such as?
Who knows?
We missed them.
But so you don't have anything kind of filed away in your brain, oh, I wish we had known.
I wish we had done so and so.
Yeah.
No, we did the best we could as far as it's concerned, probably.
There were some things that we couldn't do.
We didn't do as well as, for example, we couldn't do biochemistry as well as other places did.
We missed some things in building a strong nutrition program and a human nutrition program.
And I started because we had no history of home economics where human nutrition was in the play.
As far as you know,
when Mr. Rutter apparently decided we're going to give real emphasis to chemistry and economics.
Were there any other areas that might have gotten his attention like those two did?
No, I thought that was a good decision.
And I'm assuming he thought that agriculture engineering didn't need that special attention.
That's right.
He was looking for the future where he could make it.
If you don't mind to cut this off, I'm going to call my daughter real quick.
I don't know.
I see some things that bother me a little bit right now.
Do you want to mention what they are?
Well, I think the biggest problem that I see is that I remember the halcyon days of John Conley and Earl Rudder.
And I do mention John Conley in that particular situation, where higher education in Texas was being supported largely.
Today, higher education is squeezed.
And in the process of squeezing,
There is a beginning to be concerned among faculty members that the current organization is at fault.
And if we had a department of food science, food science would fare better.
We don't need to have the traditional animal husbandry because what we need to do is to have the scientific areas.
Let's establish genomics, animal genomics, and use the genomics of nutrition and things of the sort.
But maybe they're right.
But what bothers me fundamentally is that there is a...
a movement to establish a school of natural biosciences or natural resources, renewable natural resources.
Essentially, I tried to get such a thing called to get the Institute of Renewable Natural Resources or something of that sort years ago.

It never worked because the heads of departments and the faculty didn't want to have another administrative unit in between themselves and the administrators, that is the directors of the experiment station.
But now with the shortage of money, maybe we can get more money if we have a school.
They may be right.
But essentially, where is the future?
Who's sitting down to look at the future as far as agriculture is concerned?
Who's sitting down to look at the future as far as science is concerned?
And until the little green book says we've got to look at the future, we've got a changing future that we have to do.
So it bothers me a lot.
And the problem is the older faculty.
They don't want to change.
If you were hired as the consultant to Texas A&M University today, what advice would you give it and its leaders about moving forward?
Well, I would say,
Do what you're doing now, but still don't give up the older traditional parts of the university that may be a part of it.
In other words, sit down and look at.
And don't do it with a group of people.
Don't do it with a whole faculty.
Do it with leaders.
Do it with small groups of people.
Wherein you can have 18 people was probably a maximum number as far as the research group of the century study.
But you see, those things, those kinds of discussions aren't being done today.
And there's just as many big problems out there as there are now.
A large number of the faculty come from places that don't know about land grant universities and don't know about the service aspects of things.
And right now, with the Bush administration moving toward NIH, particularly doing the research of NIH and squeezing everything else,
How best in today's world could the research and teaching and service in agriculture, how could those functions best be put together?
Well, theoretically they're put together where they ought to be right now.
Is the current organization, is that the way you'd have it?
That's right.
But the problem is, are the people the right people?
Now, Heiler has hired two people up front, which I have a high regard for.
Charles Seifrich, he brought back, and Fuller Baser.
By the way, Fuller Basler is one of these that you have to consider as being one of the stars we brought in.
You have those two people there.
But now Extension, we don't have the same kind of leadership in Extension.
A visionary kind of thing.
All right, would you have the chief academic administrator reporting
both to the president and to the chancellor?
It can be done.
Is that the best way?
That's the best way.
What advice would you have to A&M's leadership about size?
Should A&M be larger or smaller?
in its enrollment and programming?
I wish I knew the answer to that.
As long as we were growing, we could do some things.
The minute we put a cap on, you begin to put limits and you have to set priorities.
And those priorities, are they the right priorities?
I don't know.
I don't think so.
But is there the same kind of
of unity, of feeling with 44,000 that there used to be?
Oh, no.
No.
The faculty is more independent and more dispersed.
For example, during the work day, if you wanted to walk across the campus
encounter some other faculty members, where did you go?
You want to go have coffee?
Well, I don't know.
Did you all used to go to the MSC?
We used to go to the MSC, but they don't do it anymore.
We have coffee here, as far as it's concerned.
When they designed this building, I put a lounge in here.
And with the idea that somehow the faculty could get together.
It never worked.
It didn't work because somebody wanted a living room.
They wanted a place to bring people in.
They wanted to have meeting rooms rather than societal situations.
There's this great fear that the faculty is going to get lazy and do some other things.
All right, now we're backing up.
In 1988, when you left the dean's function, did you retire at that point?
No, I came over as a full-time faculty.
As a full-time faculty.
And who succeeded you?
Charles Harnson.
Did he or anyone else ask you for any advice at that point?
As far as I know, he was advised not to seek my advice.
Oh, I see, I see.
Which I think was an error because I didn't think that, I didn't think as differently from him as some people might have.
Now, and did you have, the timing of your ceasing as dean, was that caused by your having some disagreements with somebody?
No, I was 65 years old.
Oh, so it's a 65.
Okay.
And so they decided, and basically they, okay, he's 65, we ought to get on, we need to put the dean's job and the director's job and the deputy chancellor's job, or title at least, in one place.
And those were separated at that point, I think.
And it took them a decade or so to put them back together?
I think it was all right to put them back together.
No, no, but it took them 10 years, didn't it, to put them back together?
Yes.
What have we not talked about that we should have?
I've run out of topics that I've thought of.
Well, I think I have expressed most of my feelings as far as this is concerned, most of my thinking.
I think that Texas A&M still has some possibilities.
of becoming great, it may change its character.
I really don't know what colleges of agriculture ought to be in the future.
And I'm thinking of that more than anything else.
I know what universities ought to be in the future.
And that's generally an organization without a college of agriculture.
And so colleges of agriculture who want to survive have to fit within that particular conceptual basis of being in a university as far as that's concerned.
And who has done that best?
Cornell?
I don't think anybody has done it best.
Okay.
All right.
Back to you again personally.
Individual special moments that are your greatest pleasures while you were, was it getting that watch?
Yes.
I had, of course, this was my second watch.
This was administration.
I got one as teaching.
Oh, okay.
Yes, that was it.
Recently, last fall, I was named one of the outstanding graduates of Texas A&M's College of Agriculture and Life Sciences.
That's splendid.
I think, looking back upon the Research and Extension Center concept, I think changing the name of the college to College of Agriculture and Life Sciences
And there were some things that I tried I thought were pretty good ideas, but they were quite sold.
For example, I tried to get people to think about the Master of Agriculture as a system sort of like an MBA program.
But science so dominates the thinking of faculty that
To whom do you feel greatest gratitude for your A&M years?
People that helped you, that made your work?
Well, the first person would be Pearson.
Paul Pearson.
He was the first head of the Department of Biochemistry and Nutrition.
He was dean of graduate college at that particular point.
Carl Lyman probably helped me as much as anybody.
Jack Miller.
Obviously Earl Rudder.
Leon S. Bill Pope.
Jack Williams.
I'd even listen to her in that crowd.
Alright, summarize your feelings about A&M in a sentence or so.
Well, I think it's an institution that is
